Mixed reviews of this film, some critics say he came close to his masterpiece, others say you need to have swatted up on your quantum mechanics and that the plot is quite complex. In other words - it's going to be pure awesome, and possibly an epic adventure film meant for an intelligent audience for once. Hopefully.

I'm afraid this will be another disappointing sci-fi movie, like Gravity. It will probably be filled with all sorts of misconceptions about space, even though Kip Thorne has been the scientific consultant for it (and also executive producer). Remember the movie "Sunshine" from 2007? Brian Cox was the scientific consultant for that one, and yet the movie was filled with all sorts of misconceptions and inaccuracies that made me laugh.
And what about Gravity? That unknown force that pulled Clooney away from the ISS was a total joke, same for the orbital nonsense between the Hubble, the ISS and the Russian satellites, etc.

Just so you know, Interstellar tells the story of a group of astronauts who "travel" through a black hole...with hopes of going somewhere else and then return to Earth, that is. For all science knows, the laws of physics break down inside a black hole due to the tremendous gravitational pull, that means that we can't possibly know, through physics, what happens exactly to things that cross the "event horizon" (that's the edge of the black hole, so to speak).Â 
All science can tell for sure is that when something crosses the event horizon, there's no turning back, if you somehow managed to come out, it wouldn't be alive and in one piece. When Hawking talks about how it is possible for information to be preserved inside a black hole, it just means INFORMATION, in other words, the particles that form your body could still be "preserved" somehow but you would die nonetheless, all your atoms would be undone, and that isn't pretty.
Whoever tells you that you can travel through black holes (survive the journey and come back to the same universe as if nothing happened, that is), doesn't have the math/mechanism to support this claim and Kip Thorne knows it.
I bet all Kip has done is to help model the black hole, give direction to actors who will play scientist roles and perhaps a few more things, but I'm pretty sure this movie will still contain nonsense. Sci-fi directors usually claim they've made sure everything is scientifically accurate, showing us stuff like this>Â  Interstellar â€“ Building A Black Hole â€“ Official Warner Bros.
so people can say "Oh! This time they've got it right!" when, in reality, only some things are accurate, the rest is usually nonsense. Movies like Sunshine and Gravity are clear examples of this.
Curiously, there is a 1968 movie called "2001: A Space Odyssey" (perhaps you've heard about it, LOL) that gets most things right, without the need of using unlikely black hole travel, without the need to sell it for its "realism" or scientific accuracy, without flashy special effects, absurd amounts of money and without being too pretentious.
The non-scientific parts of that movie are highly symbolic, which make it even better.

So Hollywood sci-fi movies nowadays have much larger budgets, a much higher availability of professionals from all branches, highly superior technology available, they generate much more money, etc. and yet they are worse every year... Why is that?
I think it's because the essential guidelines of the business are wrong. They go for flashiness (big names, high numbers, extreme and flashy plots, etc.) instead of quality, they try to conciliate science with nonsensical extreme plots that are completely incompatible and absurd (my point being> don't try to sell the movie for its realism and accuracy if, in the end, it won't be so).
This is the formula: big names + claims of scientific accuracy/realism + extreme plots filled with nonsense (the world is about to end, there's a critical accident/everything goes wrong, and the like) + stuff blowing up/getting destroyed + miraculous survivals + ultra hd cameras and all sorts of modern filters and effects + the hero saves the day (requiring his/her/their sacrifice, perhaps) = Next Hollywood sci-fi movie.

I love space movies, many of them are enthralling; I ardently respect all those astronauts who go to space and carry out experiments aboard the ISS. But, as a resident of this planet, I would love it if humanity would be less cruel to nature, and help maintain the balance of our ecosystem, by reducing pollution, violence, killing of animals. I am sure that no one will ever migrate to any other planet(Mars being the only option), because our body does not suit their atmosphere-if anyone goes on interplanetary travel, I am sure it will be a 1 way trip, and the whole world's population will never go, except astronauts & crazy billionaires. The Earth has life for a reason, no other planet has that, and we should be grateful for that. Wormholes are still a theory, but, if it is found to exist, interstellar travel will be carried out by astronauts only; 7 billion(who knows, 14 billion in the future) will never go and colonize on Alpha Beta whatever new planet that's discovered; we shall perish anyway due to geological events, maybe a massive earthquake, too much pollution, poisonous radiation from space etc. So, my point is, space travel should only be in fiction, novels and movies, and whatever NASA is doing, at least for now. It would be much useful for Earth & humanity's survival, if we concentrate on eradicating diseases, inventing a cure for all incurable diseases, reducing pollution of air/water/sound/land/electronic waste/radioactive waste etc., finding alternate ways of harnessing pollution free energy, letting animals live, and reducing violence, and lastly, doing all the mentioned work on a major scale(not like, only 20 cars run on electricity and the rest use gas) because, if the Earth survives, we do too-and the longer we live, the longer we can experiment on space travel. But Earth is our home and foundation, and we must not forget that.

the idea behind this film is simple, the ability to use a wormhole to jump to another planet and find a livable environment is perfectly plausible, though highly unlikely, and depending on the development of technology and the plausibility of being able to colonize mars and sustain that would not be plausible at all, we have technology to make that work for some time, but not for the 50+years this film is seeming to aim at. Interstellar travel is a fact of live and will happen eventually assuming our race evolves enough and the parameters of physics happen, due to the high likelihood that the ability of earth to sustain us as lifeforms will end. and while we may not know exactly how wormholes work in every facet, they do seem to be the best option in terms of interstellar travel out there due to the distances between solar systems being to great. this movie isn't silly, nor is it illogical based on the parameters it gives, its just exploring a thought path that we will probably explore one day. also as far as the food problem, that could very easily happen based on solar emission spectra changing in the slightest manner due to the core composition of our sun changing, so no it is not stupid, please stop talking as if you know everything in the field of astrophysics and biology, life isnt that simple.

This is what I think the plot is:Â 

Humanity faces extinction from starvation. The sun has become too unstable to sustain life on Earth for much longer. However, a wormhole has been discovered, and Earth's governments decide to send a team through the wormhole to discover where it leads to. If it is safe, humanity will begin a mass exodus through the wormhole.Â 

The main character is an engineer and a pilot, which makes him suitable for such a mission. He has two children, a daughter and a son, which he loves very much. He leaves on the mission unwillingly, promising his children that he will come back.Â 

However, years has passed. The main character's children has now grown up (Jessica Chastain plays his grown up daughter, note the similarity between the two) and Earth is in much more dire situation. The main character and his mission has not returned and the children starts looking for answers.Â

@The Ayala Factor Just to clarify, they're not going into a black hole, their space ship essentially creates a tiny one, or a singularity, to warp space-time, which allows for faster than light travel. This movie is based on real scientific theory. And though some black hole theories account for the possibility of traveling vast distances of the universe if one went through it, all one has to do is account for the sheer gravitational power of the black hole beyond the event horizon to know that its just not possible. The worm hole as seen in this trailer is a depiction of Dr. Kip Thorne's theories of a spinning black hole. Kip is a world renowned Caltech Physicist and leader of wormhole theory. Nolan brought him on as an exec prod for the film and He is taking my breath away. Not only does he depict the most realistic future apocalypse with climate change destroying soil and producing dust bowls, but he is giving us a realistic glimpse into real theoretical interstellar travel. This man knows no equal when it comes to truly inspirational a moving tales. As was so eloquently said decade ago, he is "inspiring the imagination of a generation".

Yet another silly Hollywood mess that demonstrates a complete ignorance of science and how it would be applied to avert crisis. Set to the tune of millions of wasted dollars.

If we run into the problem of critical food shortage, and we very well may, a more prudent solution would be to apply vertical farms. There are nations out there building them today. (Sadly, none of those nations are America.) We wouldn't wait until the problem has created a global dust-bowl dystopia then send a single crew to another planet. That solution, while it makes for pretty visuals and an entertaining, if silly story,Â is asinine.

I encourage people genuinely concerned with global food shortage to check out vertical farming, and particularly a book written by Mr. Diamandis and Mr. Kotler entitled: "Abundance".

I'll see this movie in theaters, but I'll bringÂ my ownÂ grain of salt.
